## 📁 What We Built — File by File

### `docker-compose.yml` — Infrastructure as Code
```yaml
services:
  postgres:    # Our relational database (users, documents, conversations)
    image: postgres:15
    ports: "5433:5432"   # ⚠️ Using 5433 because your PC already has PostgreSQL on 5432

  chromadb:    # Our vector database (stores PDF embeddings for RAG search)
    image: chromadb/chroma:latest
    ports: "8001:8000"
```

**Why Docker?** Instead of installing PostgreSQL and ChromaDB manually, Docker runs them in isolated containers. One command (`docker-compose up -d`) starts everything. When you're done, `docker-compose down` stops everything cleanly.

**Lesson Learned:** Your PC already had PostgreSQL installed on port 5432. Two programs can't share the same port, so we mapped Docker's PostgreSQL to port **5433** instead.

